A beginner-friendly and in-depth guide to understanding and using the Raspberry Pi Pico microcontroller board.
This guide covers everything from what the Pico is, how it works internally, how to program it, and what projects you can build with it.
What is Raspberry Pi Pico:
The Raspberry Pi Pico is a low-cost, high-performance microcontroller board developed by the Raspberry Pi Foundation and released in January 2021.
It is built around the RP2040, a custom chip designed entirely by Raspberry Pi.
Unlike the Raspberry Pi 4 or Raspberry Pi Zero, the Pico is not a mini computer and does not run Linux.
It is a microcontroller, similar to an Arduino, designed to control hardware components directly by running code stored in its onboard flash memory. 
It is priced at around $4 USD and measures just 51mm by 21mm.
Key Features:
The Pico is powered by the RP2040 chip, which includes a dual-core ARM Cortex-M0+ processor running at up to 133 MHz. 
It comes with 264 KB of SRAM and 2 MB of onboard QSPI flash storage.
The board provides 26 multifunction GPIO pins, 3 twelve-bit ADC inputs, 16 PWM channels, and supports communication protocols including UART, SPI, I2C, and USB 1.1.
It can operate at voltages between 1.8V and 5.5V, making it flexible for a wide range of hardware setups.
The RP2040 Microcontroller:
The heart of the Pico is the RP2040 chip, a custom silicon designed by Raspberry Pi. 
It features two ARM Cortex-M0+ cores, meaning it can run two tasks simultaneously. 
It has 264 KB of fast SRAM split into six banks for parallel access. 
One of the most unique features of the RP2040 is its Programmable I/O (PIO) system.
PIO allows you to create custom hardware communication protocols in dedicated state machines without using the main CPU. 
This is extremely useful for tasks like driving WS2812 NeoPixel LEDs, reading rotary encoders, generating VGA signals, or handling high-speed data sampling.
No other microcontroller at this price point offers this capability.
How the Pico Works:
When you write code for the Pico and flash it, the RP2040 reads that code from the flash memory and executes it directly.
The GPIO pins then respond to your code by turning on LEDs, reading sensor values, controlling motors, or communicating with other devices. 
The entire boot process begins when you hold the BOOTSEL button on the board and connect it to your computer via USB. 
The Pico appears as a USB storage drive on your computer. 
You simply drag and drop a .uf2 firmware or program file onto it, and the Pico reboots automatically and begins running your code. 
There is no operating system, no boot loader complexity, and no configuration required.
